  "prompt": "Should you rinse with water after mouthwash?",
  "response": "Rinsing with water immediately after using **mouthwash** is generally **not recommended**. Here's why:\n\n1. **Preserves Active Ingredients**: Mouthwash contains active ingredients (like fluoride, antimicrobial agents, or essential oils) that need time to work. Rinsing with water right after can wash away these beneficial components, reducing their effectiveness.\n\n2. **Maintains Benefits**: Leaving the mouthwash residue in your mouth allows it to continue fighting bacteria, freshening breath, and protecting teeth for a longer period.\n\n3. **Follow Product Instructions**: Always check the label of your specific mouthwash. Some products may explicitly advise against rinsing with water after use.\n\n### When Can You Rinse with Water?\n- If the mouthwash causes irritation or an unpleasant taste, you can rinse with water after waiting a few minutes.\n- If the product instructions recommend rinsing (though this is less common).\n\n### Best Practice:\n- Use mouthwash **after brushing and flossing**.\n- Spit out the mouthwash but **avoid rinsing with water** for at least 30 minutes to maximize its benefits.",
